MYSTERY DISEASE - HAWAII (4)
============================
[1]
Date: Fri, 8 Mar 96 11:38:45 PST
Sender: bakey@state.va.us
Sir:
In response to the RFI from Dr. Hass in Hawaii, there is an excellent
review of the "Emergence of the Ehrlichioses as Human Health Problems"
in Vol. 2, No. 1, Jan. - March of the journal "Emerging Infectious
Diseases". This journal is available electronically at the Centers for
Disease Control (CDC) at http://www.cdc.gov/. In the article the
author states that both E. chafeensis, cause of Human Monocytic
Ehrlichiosis, and the E. equi-like agent responsible for Human
Granulocytic Ehrlichiosis are carried in dogs. It is also stated that
Rhipicephalus sanguineus is the major vector of E. canis in dogs.
Ehrlichiosis in humans certainly does produce flu-like illness (or worse)
and is certainly responsive to tetracyclines. It sounds like it might be
worth some follow up serology in those patients.
Cheers,
Bruce L. Akey, M.S., D.V.M.
Chief, Office of Laboratory Services
Virginia Dept. of Agriculture and Consumer Services
-------------------------------------
E-mail: bakey.vdacs@state.va.us
Date: 03/08/96
Time: 11:38:46
