[2]
From: grenard@herpmed.com
Date: Thu, 07 Mar 1996 21:52:43 -0800 (PST)
RE: Tick Borne Diseases Zoonotically Transferred(?)
In 1978 a cluster of Q-Fever caused by Coxiella burnetti was seen in a
group of employees of an exotic bird and reptile importing company in
New York State. These employees were involved in the handling and
removal of ticks from an infested shipment of Ball Pythons (P. regius)
from Ghana. Three types of ticks were identified including
Amblyomma nuttalli, the usual vector of Q-Fever. It was determined
that the employees became ill as a result of either inhaling infected
tick excreta and/or snake excreta (since the pythons were also infected).
Refs: Yadav,MD, Sethi MS. 1979. Poikilotherms as resevoirs of Q fever
(Coxiella burnetti) in Uttr Pradesh. J. Wildlife Diseases 15:15.
Frye,FL. 1991. Biomedical and SUrgical Aspects of Captive Reptile
Husbandry (pp 101-160). Krieger Publishing, Malabar, FL
Mader,D(ed). 1995. Reptile Medicine and Surgery. p.26. WB Saunders,
Philadelphia.
Steve Grenard
